Macedonians in referendum on changing the country's name
In a referendum on Sunday, the Macedonians voted to change the name of the country to the 'Republic of North Macedonia', which would resolve a decades-long dispute with Greece, which has blocked the country's aspirations to join the European Union and NATO.
In the view of Greece, which owns the province of Macedonia, the name of the northern neighbour is in practice a territorial requirement for its territory and has therefore opposed its accession to the EU and NATO.
In June, the governments of the two countries reached an agreement on a new name proposal, but anti-nationalists believe that the change would weaken the ethnic identity of the Slavic majority in Macedonia.
President Gjorge Ivanov has announced that he will not vote in the referendum, and the campaign against the vote raises doubts as to whether the required 50 % turnout will be reached in order for the result to be legal.
The question on the ballot was: “Are you on the side of NATO and EU membership, accepting the agreement with Greece?”
Proponents of the name change, such as Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, argue that it is worth paying the price so that Macedonia, which emerged from the collapse of Yugoslavia, can apply for both EU and NATO membership. .
"I came today to vote for the future of our country, for the young Macedonians, so that they can live in freedom as members of the European Union, because it means a safer life for all of us," said 79-year-old Olivera Georgievska in Skopje.
Although the vote is not legally binding, enough Members of this House have said that they respect the result of the vote in order to have a decisive effect.
A change of name requires a two-thirds majority in Parliament.
According to the Central Election Commission, no irregularities had been reported by 1 p.m.
However, the turnout was only 16 per cent, compared to 34 per cent in the last parliamentary elections in 2016, when 66 per cent of voters voted.
"I came to vote for my children and for our place in Europe," said 62-year-old Gjose Tanevski, who voted in the capital Skopje.
Macedonian Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, his wife Zorica and son Dushko voted in a referendum on the name change of Macedonia in Strumica, Macedonia, on 30 September 2018.
54-year-old Vladimir Kavardarkov prepared a small stage and placed chairs in front of the tents erected to boycott the referendum in front of the Skopje Parliament.
"We support NATO and the EU, but we want to join with our heads upright, not through the kitchen door," Kavadarkov said.
"We are a poor country, but we have dignity.
If they don’t want to take us as Macedonia, we can turn elsewhere, like China and Russia, as part of Euro-Asia integration.”
Prime Minister Zaev said NATO membership would bring much-needed investment to Macedonia, which has an unemployment rate of over 20%.
"I believe that a large majority will vote in favour of the name change because more than 80% of our citizens are in favour of the EU and NATO," Zaev said.
He said "yes" is "the way we see our future."
A poll published Monday by the Macedonian Institute for Political Studies indicated a turnout of 30-43% in the referendum - that is, below the required level of activity.
In a second survey commissioned by Macedonia’s Telma TV, 57% of respondents planned to vote on Sunday.
Seventy percent of them said they would vote for the “yes” option.
For a referendum to be successful, voter turnout must exceed 50% by one vote.
