The learning outcomes of private schools in Scotland have traditionally been good, and this success has continued in 2018 as a result of good exam results. The success has been strengthened by individual and community success in sports, art, music and other community projects.
These schools of more than 30,000 pupils across Scotland, represented by SCIS, the Scottish Council of Private Schools, aim to provide a high level of service to their pupils and their parents.
Private schools strive to prepare their students for careers of their choice, postgraduate and higher education, and global citizenship.
As an educational actor who can design and implement tailor-made learning content, we have noticed the status of languages as a popular and desirable subject to continue in educational institutions.
Nelson Mandela once said, “If you speak to a person in a language he understands, the message goes to his head.
If you speak to a person in his or her own language, the message will go to his or her heart.”
This is a strong reminder that we cannot rely solely on the English language if we want to build relationships with people in other countries with confidence.
This year’s latest test results show that languages are at the top of the list in terms of passing rates among private schools.
Sixty-eight per cent of students studying foreign languages achieved the highest A score.
The data was collected from 74 SCIS schools and found that 72% of the students with the highest A score studied Mandarin, 72% studied German, 69% studied French and 63% studied Spanish.
This shows that private schools in Scotland support the study of foreign languages as an essential skill that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages are currently optional subjects, but they are considered to be of the same value as natural science subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics), both in the study programme of private schools and elsewhere.
A 2014 survey commissioned by the UK Employment Agency found that 17% of situations where an employer had difficulty finding a suitable employee were explained by a lack of language skills.
The development of language skills is therefore even more necessary for the future career development of young people.
The more language skills are required for possible work tasks, the more relevant these skills are in the global world.
If a person has studied a second language, he will have an advantage over this lifelong skill in the future, regardless of the career he has chosen.
The ability to communicate directly with a foreigner automatically puts a multilingual person ahead of the competition.
According to a survey conducted by YouGov in 2013, 75 percent of more than 4,000 British adults are unable to communicate in a foreign language, and French was the only two-digit language spoken by 15 percent.
This is why investing in language teaching is important for today’s children.
Especially knowledge of the languages of developing countries gives children a better opportunity to find meaningful careers.
Within Scotland, schools differ in the languages they teach.
Several schools focus on traditional languages, while some specifically teach languages that are supposed to be important to the UK in 2020, such as Mandarin Chinese and Japanese.
Despite your child’s interests, private schools always have several language options taught by specialised teachers.
Private schools in Scotland are dedicated to providing a learning environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills needed to succeed in whatever the future holds.
At this time, it cannot be denied that in the international business environment, languages will continue to be very important for the future of the country, so this must be reflected in education.
Modern languages should indeed be seen as "international communication skills".
Private schools will continue to offer this freedom of choice, versatility and high-level youth in Scotland.
Il faut bien le faire.
John Edward is the head of SCIS, Scottish Private Schools Council.
