Harvard Students Take Adequate Rest Instruction Course
This year, all undergraduate students at Harvard University will take part in a course designed to increase students’ rest. This course is a counter-attack to the university’s thriving macho culture, where students weigh long nights with the power of caffeine.
According to the researcher, students at the best university in the world are often quite unaware of the basic issues related to their own well-being.
Designed by Charles Czeisler, a professor of medicine at Harvard University who works on sleep research at Brigham and Women's Hospital, the course is believed to be the first of its kind in the United States.
Czeisler got the idea for the course after giving a lecture on the effect of sleep deprivation on learning.
"After the lecture, a young woman came to me and said, 'Why do I hear about it only now, in my final year of school?'
No one had ever told him about the need for sleep, which was surprising to me," he said in an interview with the Telegraph.
For the first time this year, the course will guide students on how proper sleep habits support academic and athletic performance and improve overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of medicine at Harvard University and deputy director of health services at the university, says the university ended up organizing the course after hearing how students suffered from severe sleep deficiencies during the week of study.
The one-hour course includes a set of interactive assignments.
In one section, students are presented with a picture of a dorm room where the student can click on coffee cups, curtains, sports equipment and books, thereby gaining information about the effects of caffeine and light, as well as the effect of sleep deficiency on sports performance and the importance of regular evening activities.
The second section explains how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression and cancer.
A campus map with interactive icons encourages participants to reflect on their daily routines.
“We know that this does not have an immediate impact on student behavior.
We believe, however, that they have the right to know about these things in exactly the same way as they have the right to know about the health effects of smoking," Professor Czeisler adds.
According to Professor Czeisler, all-night study marathons are still a subject of pride, and modern technology and the ever-increasing pressure on students made sleep deprivation a growing problem.
“Getting adequate and high-quality sleep should be the students’ ‘secret weapon’ against stress, exhaustion, and anxiety, and even weight gain, because sleep deprivation causes a state in the brain that is similar to starvation, which is why people are constantly hungry,” the professor notes.
Raymond So, a Californian 19-year-old student of chemical and physical psychology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course after attending one of the courses he taught in his first year at Harvard last year.
He says the course opened his eyes and gave an impetus to the organisation of a comprehensive course for all students on the campus.
He hopes that all postgraduate students could complete a similar course of study before moving to a competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler advises students to set an alarm clock to remind them of their bedtime in addition to waking up in the morning, and to keep in mind the adverse effects of electronic displays and LED lighting "blue light" on the circadian rhythm, which can make it more difficult to fall asleep.
