New cancer vaccine is able to teach the immune system to ‘see’ malignant cells
New cancer vaccine is able to teach the immune system to ‘see’ malignant cells and destroy them
Vaccine teaches the immune system to recognize malignant cells as part of treatment
In this method, resistant cells are isolated from the patient and modified in the laboratory
After treatment, the cells injected back into the body are able to ‘see’ the proteins typical of many cancers
The dog vaccine has yielded promising results in patients with different types of cancer.
For example, cancer cells in a patient with ovarian cancer disappeared within 18 months after being treated with a vaccine that teaches the immune system to recognize malignant cells.
The method is to isolate resistant cells from the patient and modify them in the laboratory so that they are able to ‘see’ the HER2 proteins typical of many cancers, and then inject the modified cells back into the body.
Professor Jay Berzofsky of the National Cancer Institute in Bethesda, U.S.A., describes the method: “Our findings suggest that this is a very promising vaccine.”
HER2 "controls the growth of several types of cancer," Professor Berzofsky explains. "These include breast cancer, as well as cancers of the ovaries, lungs, and colon."
A similar approach —to take resistant cells from the patient and teach them how to attack cancer cells— has also produced results in the treatment of one type of leukaemia.
