HIV/AIDS: New infections in China increased by 14%
China has reported an increase of 14% in the number of its HIV-positive and AIDS-infected citizens.
Health officials say the virus affects the lives of more than 820,000 people in the country.
Approximately 40,000 new cases have been reported in the second quarter of 2018 alone.
The overwhelming majority of new cases have been transmitted through sex, which represents a change in previous statistics.
Traditionally, HIV has spread rapidly in some parts of China through contaminated blood transfusions.
However, according to Chinese health officials at a conference in Yunnan province, HIV infections in this way have been reduced to almost zero.
A year later, however, the number of people infected with HIV and AIDS in China has risen by 100,000 cases.
HIV transmission through sex is an acute issue in China’s LGBT community.
Homosexuality was decriminalized in China in 1997, but discrimination against LGBT people has been reported to be widespread.
Studies have estimated that, due to conservative values in the country, 70-90% of men who have sex with men eventually marry women.
Many diseases are caused by inadequate protection in such relationships.
Since 2003, the Chinese government has pledged to guarantee universal access to HIV medicines as part of efforts to address the problem.
