What is the Global Citizen Festival and what has it done to reduce poverty?
The Global Citizen Festival, which will be held in New York on Saturday, is a music event with performers as impressive as its mission: eradicating poverty in the world.
The seventh Global Citizen Festival will attract tens of thousands of people to the lawns of Central Park in New York City to listen to performers such as Janet Jackson, Cardi B and Shawn Mendes, but also to make the real goal of the event known: eradicating extreme poverty by 2030.
Launched in 2012, the Global Citizen Festival is a continuation of the Global Powerty Project, an international advisory group whose goal is to eradicate poverty by increasing the number of people actively working to eradicate poverty.
In order to receive a free ticket for an event (if you are not willing to pay for a VIP ticket), the audience must perform various tasks or “deeds”, such as volunteering, sending an email to a political decision-maker or making a phone call, or performing any other act that raises awareness of the goals of the project.
But how has Global Citizen succeeded now that it has only 12 years to reach its goal?
Is the idea of rewarding people with a free concert ticket a real way to persuade people to take action, or is it just one ‘clictivism’ among others – the idea that you can change the world by signing an online address or sending a tweet?
Global Citizen has reported over 19 million "deeds" since 2011.
These actions have encouraged policymakers to declare commitments and principles equivalent to more than <0x24>37 billion, which have been spent in a way that will affect the lives of more than 2.25 billion people by 2030.
In early 2018, the group listed 390 commitments and statements on the basis of which more than <0x24>10 billion has already been spent or raised.
The group estimates that the funds so far have affected the lives of nearly 649 million people worldwide.
Key commitments include, for example, The Power of Nutrition, a UK-based group of investors and executives committed to “helping children develop to their full potential”. The group committed to deliver <0x24>35 million to Rwanda to end malnutrition in the country. This was after activists sent them 4,700 tweets as a result of the Global Citizen campaign.
“Thanks to the British government, donors, governments of different countries, and the world’s citizens just like you, we are able to pass social injustice and malnutrition to the journals of history,” Power of Nutrition Ambassador Tracey Ullman told the audience at a concert in London in 2018.
The group also called on the British government to take action to improve the nutrition of mothers and children through more than 5,000 actions. The government has announced funding for the Power on Nutrition project, which focuses on combating malnutrition and reaches 5 million mothers and children.
One of the most frequently asked questions on the movement’s website is: “Why do you think we can end extreme poverty?”
Global Citizen’s response: “The road will be long and difficult and there will be many stumbling blocks in front of us.
But we will succeed, like the great civil rights struggles and anti-apartheid movements before us, because together we are stronger.”
Deborra-Lee Furness and Hugh Jackman will host the New York Concert this year, and its starring cast includes artists such as Janet Jackson, the Weeknd, Shawn Mendes, Cardi B and Janelle Monáe.
