World Wide Web inventor plans to launch a new Internet as a counterattack to Google and Facebook
Tim Berners-Lee, inventor of the World Wide Web, has launched a startup company that aims to compete with Facebook, Amazon and Google.
The latest project of the technology legend, Inrupt, is a company based on Berners-Lee’s open-source Solid platform.
Solid allows users to decide where their information is stored and who has access to what information.
In an interview with the Fast Company, Berners-Lee jokes that Inrupt’s goal is “to rule the world.”
"It has to be done now," he said, referring to his startup.
“This is a historic moment.”
The application uses Solid’s technology to allow people to create their own “personal data repository” or POD.
It can include contact lists, memory lists, calendar, music library, and other personal and professional tools.
It’s like Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify all available in one browser at the same time.
What is unique about a personal data repository is that it is entirely up to the user who has access to what kind of data.
The company calls it “personal empowerment through information.”
According to the company’s CEO, John Bruce, the idea behind Inrupt is to provide the resources, processes and skills needed to make Solid accessible to everyone.
The company currently includes Berners-Lee, Bruce, an IBM-acquired security platform, a community of hired developers working on the project, and a community of volunteer coders.
Technology developers around the world can create their own decentralized applications using the tools available on Inrupt’s website. All this will be available from this week.
Berners-Lee says he and his team will not discuss with Facebook and Google whether or not people should be offered a complete change where all their business models are turned upside down overnight.
“We’re not asking for their consent.”
In a paper published in Medium on Saturday, Berners-Lee wrote that Inrupt's "mission is to provide commercial energy and an ecosystem for the coherence and quality of the new network built on Solid."
In 1994, Berners-Lee revolutionized the Internet by setting up the World Wide Web Consortium at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
In recent months, Berners-Lee has been an influential voice in the debate on net neutrality.
Berners-Lee will continue to be the founder and leader of the World Wide Web Consortium, Web Foundation and Open Data Institute even after the launch of Inrupt.
"I am extremely optimistic about the next era of the network," Berners-Lee added.
